video_name: New York governor's ex-aide charged as Chinese spy | BBC News
title: New York governor's ex-aide charged as Chinese spy | BBC News
video_description:
A former deputy chief of staff to New York Governor Kathy Hochul has been charged with acting as an agent of the Chinese government.

Linda Sun has been accused of acting as an agent for Beijing in return for millions of dollars, special home deliveries of salted duck and other perks.

Prosecutors said she and Christopher Hu, her husband and co-defendant, used their ill-gotten gains to purchase real estate and luxury vehicles.

The couple pleaded not guilty to the charges against them in a Brooklyn federal court on Tuesday.

video_name: Seven swing states set to decide the 2024 US election | BBC News
title: Seven swing states set to decide the 2024 US election | BBC News
video_description:
About 240 million people are eligible to vote in this year’s US election, but only a relatively small number of them are likely to settle the question of who becomes the next president.
 
Experts believe there are only a handful of states that could plausibly be won by Kamala Harris or Donald Trump, for the Democrats or Republicans respectively.
 
Seven of them - Arizona, Georgia, Michigan, Nevada, North Carolina, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin - could hold the key to the White House.
 
Now, in the final months of the election, both campaigns are at full throttle to win over undecided voters in these states.

video_name: Six children and pregnant woman among 12 dead as boat sinks in English channel | BBC News
title: Six children and pregnant woman among 12 dead as boat sinks in English channel | BBC News
video_description:
At least 12 people have drowned after a boat carrying migrants sank off the French coast in the English Channel.  A pregnant woman was among those who died.   Six of those who lost their lives were children. 

The French coast guard said more than 50 people were rescued off the Gris-Nez cape, near the town of Boulogne-sur-Mer. Two were said to be in critical condition.   The migrants were reported to be from east Africa.

The French authorities said the boat was overloaded and only a handful of those on board had life jackets. The disaster is the deadliest loss of life in the Channel this year.

Clive Myrie presents BBC News at Ten reporting by Andrew Harding.

video_name: WHO exceeds target for Gaza polio vaccinations as campaign continues | BBC News
title: WHO exceeds target for Gaza polio vaccinations as campaign continues | BBC News
video_description:
The World Health Organization (WHO) says polio vaccinations of children in central Gaza have "surpassed the target" in the first two days of its immunisation campaign.
 
Dr Rik Peeperkorn, the UN agency's representative in the Palestinian territories, said 161,030 children under the age of 10 were vaccinated on Sunday and Monday - above the projection of 156,500.
 
The difference was probably the result of an underestimate of the population crowded into the area, he explained.
 
Israel and Hamas agreed to a series of localised pauses in the fighting to allow health workers to administer vaccines after Gaza's first confirmed case of polio in 25 years left a 10-month-old partially paralysed last month.

video_name: Netanyahu calls UK arms suspension to Israel ‘shameful’ | BBC News
title: Netanyahu calls UK arms suspension to Israel ‘shameful’ | BBC News
video_description:
The UK has defended its decision to suspend some arms sales to Israel.
 
On 2 September, it suspended around 30 out of 350 weapons export licences to Israel, saying there is a "clear risk" the equipment could be used to commit serious violations of international law.
 
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu called the decision "shameful", saying on social media that it "will only embolden Hamas".
 
But UK Defence Secretary John Healey insisted the UK remained a "staunch ally" of Israel, telling the BBC Israel's security would not be weakened by the decision.
 
Husam Zomlot, the Palestinians' top envoy to the UK, called the partial ban an “important first step” to the UK’s fulfilment of its “legal obligations under domestic and international law”.

video_description:
Pope Francis has landed in the Indonesian capital Jakarta, kicking off the longest and farthest trip of his tenure to the Asia Pacific region.
 
He is expected to highlight environmental concerns and the importance of interfaith dialogue during the 12 day trip, which will also see him travel to Papua New Guinea, Singapore and Timor-Leste.
 
He is only the third pope to visit Indonesia, which has the largest population of Muslims globally.
 
It is a particularly challenging journey for the 87-year-old, who has been battling a series of health issues.

Brazil's Supreme Court has upheld a ban on social media platform X, formerly known as Twitter.

title: UK suspends some arms exports to Israel | BBC News
video_description:
UK Foreign Secretary David Lammy has announced that the UK is suspending approximately 30 export licences for military equipment, following its review of Israel’s compliance with international humanitarian law in the course of its military operations in Gaza.
 
The 30 licences (out of a total of around 350) include components for military aircraft, helicopters, drones and items which facilitate ground targeting. Officials say the government has concluded there is a clear risk that items exported to Israel might be used in serious violations of international humanitarian law.
 
Officials emphasise that this is not an arms embargo and that the government’s assessment is not designed to prejudge the outcomes of work by international courts, such as the ICJ and ICC.

video_name: Ukrainian army's newest recruits prepare for war | BBC News
title: Ukrainian army's newest recruits prepare for war | BBC News
video_description:
Ukraine is experiencing huge pressure on its eastern home front, as it grapples with the sheer mass of men Russia has committed to the frontline.
 
The Ministry of Defence in London estimated there were 70,000 Russian casualties in Ukraine in May and June alone.

Two and a half years into the war, and Ukraine is desperate for more troops.
New army joiners are undergoing an accelerated programme, and it brought into force a new conscription law which lowered the age of men joining from 27 to 25. 

The drive for younger conscripts has not hit this group of men; most of the new recruits are older.

The BBC has been brought to a secret training location in the Chernihiv region where the latest army intake is being fast tracked to the battlefield in the renewed effort to blunt Moscow’s grinding advance.

video_name: Calls to reject far-right AfD party after victory in eastern Germany | BBC News
title: Calls to reject far-right AfD party after victory in eastern Germany | BBC News
video_description:
The German chancellor Olaf Scholz has urged mainstream parties not to lend support for Alternative for Germany (AfD), the first far-right party projected to win a state election since the second world war.
 
The AfD won almost a third of the vote in the eastern state of Thuringia - putting the party nine points ahead of the conservative CDU, and far in front of Germany's three governing parties.
 
The AfD's top candidate in Thuringia, Björn Höcke, who is a highly controversial figure in Germany, hailed a "historic victory" and spoke of his great pride. He failed to win a direct mandate for the state parliament, but secured a seat because he was top of his party list.
 
Mr Höcke's party has been designated as right-wing extremist and he has been fined for using a Nazi slogan, although the former history teacher denies knowingly doing so.
 
The result gives the far right its first win in a state parliament election since World War Two, although it has little hope of forming a government in Thuringia because other parties are unlikely to work with it.

The call for a one-day strike on Monday was issued by Israel's biggest labour union, Histadrut, whose leader, Arnon Bar-David, said the country was getting "body bags instead of a deal".

video_name: Huge protests in Israel as public demand deal to release hostages | BBC News
title: Huge protests in Israel as public demand deal to release hostages | BBC News
video_description:
Tens of thousands of people have rallied across Israel after the bodies of six hostages held by Hamas in the Gaza Strip were recovered by soldiers, causing national outrage.

Protesters, many clad in Israeli flags, descended on cities including Tel Aviv and Jerusalem, demanding that their government reaches a deal to secure the release of the remaining hostages taken by Hamas during the 7 October attacks.

The protests were largely peaceful but in Tel Aviv crowds broke through police lines, blocking a main highway. The demonstrations came as on of Israel's biggest labour unions, Histadrut, called for a nationwide general strike, demanding that the government reach a deal with Hamas. 

The Israel Defense Forces (IDF) said earlier that the six bodies were found in an underground tunnel in the Rafah area of southern Gaza.  The hostages were identified as Carmel Gat, Eden Yerushalmi, Hersh Goldberg-Polin, Alexander Lobanov, Almog Sarusi and Master Sgt Ori Danino.  The IDF said they had been killed shortly before its troops reached them.

News of the deaths fuelled the protests, with many Israelis accusing their government of not doing enough to secure the release of the remaining hostages.

Jane Hill presents BBC News at Ten reporting by Lucy Williamson in Jerusalem.

video_name: Ozempic could delay ageing, researchers suggest | BBC News
title: Ozempic could delay ageing, researchers suggest | BBC News
video_description:
A drug used to treat Type 2 diabetes and obesity could also slow down the process of ageing, researchers believe.

Semaglutide, better known as Ozempic, "has far-reaching benefits beyond what we initially imagined," Prof Harlan Krumholz, from the Yale School of Medicine, said following the publication of several new studies.

They found that the drug could be used to treat a wide range of illnesses linked to heart failure, arthritis, Alzheimer's and even cancer.

The new data has been published in a number of medical journals, including the Journal of the American College of Cardiology (JACC), which Prof Krumholz edits.

video_name: Oasis tickets 'must not mislead' fans', says the UK Advertising Standards Authority | BBC News
title: Oasis tickets 'must not mislead' fans', says the UK Advertising Standards Authority | BBC News
video_description:
Earlier this week standing price tickets for Cardiff, London and Edinburgh were advertised as £135 plus fees. But angry fans said online they noted "in demand" pricing on Ticketmaster had increased prices to £355 plus fees.

Ticketmaster say they do not set ticket prices.

A link on its website states: "Promoters and artists set ticket prices. Prices can be either fixed or market-based. Market-based tickets are labelled as 'Platinum' or 'In Demand'."

Ticketmaster confirmed that fans don't get anything else for the price increase.

The Advertising Standards Authority (ASA) told the BBC it could not pass comment on Ticketmaster's pricing in this instance.

“We encourage anyone with concerns to get in touch with us and we’d carefully assess whether there were any grounds for action,” an ASA spokesperson said.

But they added: “Our rules (the Advertising Codes) are clear – quoted prices must not mislead.”

video_description:
Israel says it has killed the head of the Palestinian armed group Hamas in Jenin and two other fighters, as its major military operations continue for a third day in the occupied West Bank.

Israeli security forces shot dead Wissam Khazem and then launched  air strikes on the other two men as they attempted to flee, a statement said.

The Palestinian health ministry said the three men were killed overnight near the town of Zababdeh, south-east of Jenin. Hamas also confirmed their deaths.

At least 20 Palestinians have been killed since the start of the Israeli operation, which is one of the biggest in the West Bank in two decades, according to the Palestinian health ministry.  The operation has attracted international criticism, with concerns raised over civilian casualties and the destruction of infrastructure.

The mother of a 13-year-old-British girl who died after a severe reaction to a Costa Coffee hot chocolate says she wants to make sure no other parent loses their child in the same way.

Hannah Jacobs died within hours of taking a sip of the drink in February last year.

Her mother Abimbola Duyile is calling on the food industry to take allergy training more seriously, and says she “lies awake at night” wondering if she could have prevented her death.

video_name: Israel agrees pauses in Gaza fighting to allow polio vaccination of children | BBC News
title: Israel agrees pauses in Gaza fighting to allow polio vaccination of children | BBC News
video_description:
Israel has agreed to a series of “humanitarian pauses” in Gaza to allow for the vaccination of children against polio, the World Health Organisation has said.

The campaign will aim to vaccinate around 640,000 children across the Gaza strip. It will be rolled out in three separate stages, across the central, southern and northern parts of the strip. During each stage, fighting will pause for three consecutive days between 06:00 and 15:00 local time.

The agreement comes days after UN officials said a 10-month-old baby had been partially paralysed after contracting Gaza’s first case of polio for 25 years.

The campaign will be administered by Palestinian health ministry in Gaza in collaboration with the World Health Organisation and UNICEF.

The WHO is aiming to achieve 90% vaccine coverage across the strip, the level needed to stop transmission of the virus within Gaza.

Polio is highly infectious and is most often spread through sewage and contaminated water. It can cause disfigurement and paralysis and can be fatal. 

Clive Myrie presents BBC News at Ten reporting by Lucy Williamson.

video_name: Venezuelan opposition figure faces arrest warrant | BBC News
title: Venezuelan opposition figure faces arrest warrant | BBC News
video_description:
There has been turmoil in Venezuela since the announcement of a disputed election result that handed a third consecutive term in power to President Nicolás Maduro.

The opposition says the result is fraudulent and that its candidate, Edmundo González, won the election by a wide margin. Gonzalez faces an arrest warrant for questioning over alleged election fraud.

The lawyer of Venezuelan opposition leader María Corina Machado has been detained. Perkins Rocha also serves as legal adviser for the opposition Vente Venezuela party.

He is the latest person with links to the opposition to be seized in the aftermath of last month's presidential election.

The government of Maduro has detained more than 2,400 people over the past month, creating what the UN has called "a climate of fear".

video_name: China committed to ‘stable relationship’ with US says President Xi | BBC News
title: China committed to ‘stable relationship’ with US says President Xi | BBC News
video_description:
US National Security Adviser Jake Sullivan has met with Chinese President Xi Jinping on a trip to Beijing.
 
The Chinese president said his country was committed to maintaining its relations with the United States. 
 
US National Security Adviser Jake Sullivan held a news conference after his meeting saying his role was, “responsible management of this relationship so that competition did not lead veer into confrontation”.
 
BBC’s China correspondent Laura Bicker outlined that one of the  main issues to come out of the conference was there may be one last meeting between President Biden and Xi Jingping before the end of Biden’s presidency.

video_name: UN calls for de-escalation as Israeli West Bank raids continue | BBC News
title: UN calls for de-escalation as Israeli West Bank raids continue | BBC News
video_description:
There have been conflicting death tolls as Israel's operation unfolded across multiple cities.

The IDF said yesterday that nine militants had been killed, five in Jenin and Tulkarm, and four in al-Faraa refugee camp. The Palestinian health ministry said on Thursday that 12 people had been killed in IDF attacks so far.

UN Secretary General Antonio Guterres has called on Israel to immediately halt its operation, saying it was "fuelling an already explosive situation".

He urged Israeli forces to "exercise maximum restraint and use lethal force only when it is strictly unavoidable".

The IDF said the five Palestinians were killed after "exchanges of fire" in Tulkarm.

video_name: When will Sunita Williams and Butch Wilmore return to earth? SpaceX to Rescue | India Today
title: When will Sunita Williams and Butch Wilmore return to earth? SpaceX to Rescue | India Today
video_description:
NASA astronauts Sunita Williams and Butch Wilmore have been stranded in space for four months due to multiple issues with the Boeing Starliner spacecraft. Initially an eight-day mission, the trip has been extended to early 2025. The spacecraft faced thruster malfunctions and propellant valve failures. NASA has now decided that the astronauts will return to Earth with SpaceX's Crew 9 mission in February 2025, while the Starliner will return uncrewed. The astronauts have reported strange noises from the spacecraft and face health issues due to their prolonged stay.

video_name: India Shines at Paris Paralympics with 20 Medals | Record-Shattering Performance By India's Heroes!
title: India Shines at Paris Paralympics with 20 Medals | Record-Shattering Performance By India's Heroes!
video_description:

Javelin throwers Ajeet Singh and Sundar Singh Gurjar won silver and bronze in the F46 category, while Mariyappan Thangavelu secured his third Paralympic medal, a bronze in the men's high jump T63. However, ace shooter Avani Lekhara finished fifth in the women's 50m rifle 3 positions SH1 but celebrated her consecutive gold in the 10m air rifle.

video_description:

The official anthem for the FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup Colombia 2024, titled "AHEH AHEH." This dynamic track is the result of an extraordinary collaboration between some of the most influential names in Latin music: the legendary Mambo Kings, visionary producer DJ Luian, Parker Ighile and the rising talents of Nath and Ysa. "AHEH AHEH" captures the essence of empowerment, resilience, and unity—values that are at the heart of the FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup. With pulsating beats, vibrant melodies, and powerful vocals, this anthem is more than just a song; it's a celebration of the athleticism, determination, and joy that define the future stars of football.

title: Bulbul ‪@Satinder-Sartaaj | Beat Minister | Official Video | Romantic Song | New Punjabi Songs 2024
video_description:
Immerse yourself in the soulful melody of "Bulbul," a mesmerizing Punjabi romantic song by Satinder Sartaaj, with music by Beat Minister.

Credits:-

Singer, Composer & Lyricist : Satinder Sartaaj 
Music : Beat Minister
Mix & Master : Sameer Charegaonkar 
Female Lead : Anmol Ghuman
Edit & DI : Garry Rajowal 
DOP/ Cinematographer : Lovedeep ( Brocam Films )
Producer / Director : Satinder Sartaaj

Lyrics:-

Bulbul keh gayi si mausaman da picha ni karida.  
Ohne auna jado auna aivein hauka ni bharida.  

Jado cheta aaya Chet nu taan soorje nu dassin,  
Hawa phullan nu hasau tu vi naal-naal hassin,  
Kosi aasaan waali dhup nu vi mutthiyan 'ch kassin,  
Lambi yaadan waali raatdi 'ch eda ni thharida.  

Yaad auniyan zyada vekhin assu vich gallan,  
Chitt karuga ke kunjaan naal door udd challan,  
Ja ke baddlaan de nede koi sunni jagah mallan,  
Soohi shaam nu sunaavin kissa khaaban di pari da.  

Bada hunda e farebi jeha Phaggan mahina,  
Dekhin reejhaan waali mundari 'cho digge na nageena,  
Ese rutt vich russdi jaan manndi Sakeena,  
Rakhin saanbh ke nishaani ohda kapda zari da.  

Ikk Saavan waali rutt da taan koi ni ilaaj,  
Hunde shaayaraana ese rutte piyaaran de mizaaj,  
Taanhi ishqe nu lafzaan 'ch bhare Sartaj,  
Odo paani dian kaagzaan 'te jazba dharida!

What Is LoFi ? 
Lo-fi ( low-fi) is short for low fidelity music. It is a music or production quality in which elements usually regarded as imperfections of a recording or performance are audible, are deliberately used as aesthetic choice. Some of these sounds are Vinyl Crackles, Pitch bending etc. These songs are very good for focus playlists or Study playlists.

video_name: 100 HOURS IN BAGHDAD IN 2024
title: 100 HOURS IN BAGHDAD IN 2024
video_description:
Hi friends, it would mean the world if you supported our ability to keep making videos like this one and our fundraising efforts here through Seek Discomfort's new drop live now:
🌎 For US & Worldwide (minus Europe): https://www.seekdiscomfort.com/
🌍 For Europe: https://eu.seekdiscomfort.com/

Thanks to our fantastic guide and friend Aya Salih @aya__0_0/@safraty__ for making that trip so memorable. Don't hesitate to reach out to her if you ever want to travel to Baghdad. 

Then just a note from Thomas here, I am super grateful and humbled to have the ability to create and share stories like this one. I know this isn’t the most algorithm-optimized, easy to consume, but I do feel that we need more stories like this more than the mindless YouTube challenge content. So I do hope it resonates with you and that it can, as I say in the video, build a bridge or plant a seed for empathy within us. I appreciate any and all of your support whatever it looks like from liking, commenting or buying some Seek, all of it goes a lot further than you can imagine. Much love to you all, see you on the next one.

Thank you to Aya for taking us, follow and contact her here:

video_name: WORLD’S FIRST IRON MAN IN ANTARCTICA ❄️ Project Iceman Film
title: WORLD’S FIRST IRON MAN IN ANTARCTICA ❄️ Project Iceman Film
video_description:
Don’t forget to turn on cc/subtitles. The film is translated into 10 languages. 

Thanks to the 4,212 people in our community, representing 72 countries, who backed this film and allowed us to fund post-production and bring it to life.

Thanks to 6,500+ people attending all-sold-out premieres in 12 cities on 4 different continents.

And thanks to the thousands of you, who purchased the film online knowing that it will come out on YouTube for free, but still wanted to support the project.

You’ve all enabled this historic release and allowed us to post it for free for everyone, everywhere around the world to enjoy without restrictions.

The film has won:
- Best Doc & Special Jury Award at Riviera International Film Festival 2023
- Best Doc at Rome Independent Film Awards 2023
- Best Picture & Best Doc at Los Angeles Film Awards 2023

About the film:
Project Iceman is the odyssey of an ordinary human setting out to achieve the extraordinary.

Anders Hofman attempts to become the first-ever human to complete a long-distance triathlon in Antarctica (3.8 km swim, 180 km bike, 42.2 km run), “the Iceman”, to show that limitations are perceptions.

In this death-defying journey, we witness how Anders conquers his fears, doubts, and adversities as he risks everything in one of the most extreme athletic feats ever attempted.

It’s a triumph of human potential and spirit, showing that we all can achieve anything we set our minds to.

A FILM BY YES THEORY

DIRECTED BY AMMAR KANDIL (Ammar)

VISION BY ANDERS HOFMAN
(Follow his next dream on https://www.instagram.com/andershofman — find out what he’s doing now)

video_name: The Man Who Provided Proof UFOs Are Real 🛸(Under Oath in Congress)
title: The Man Who Provided Proof UFOs Are Real 🛸(Under Oath in Congress)
video_description:
Thank you for watching and being here, and I hope we manage to spark your curiosity about the phenomenon. And deepen your empathy towards the humans who experienced it. This has been one of the greatest journeys of seeking discomfort I have ever embarked on. I hope you take some time to keep exploring, as I did three years ago. 

With love, Ammar Kandil. 

For media inquiries: media@yestheory.com 

A film by Yes Theory
In collaboration with Jesse Michels 

Directed by 
Ammar Kandil 

Director of Post Production
Thomas Dajer 

Featuring: 
David Grusch 
Staffan Taylor 
Dr Gary Nolan 
Sky Cowans 
Melanie Kirchdorfer

Cinematography by:
Shawn Malangyaon
Luke Gaie 
Bryan Felber
lan Leach

Additional footage by: 
Mario Kidd

Edited by: 
Thomas Dajer 
Cam Peddle

Assistant editor: 
Harrison King

Horse With No Name cover by Jack Gaughan
Moonchild by Psylo - https://open.spotify.com/track/3lgLnNAO6bYnpBow5RB8TR?si=ce6f1b7b84d34fde

This doc is dedicated to all truth seekers out there. 

Special thanks to:
Dr. John Mack
James Fox
Leslie Kean 
Lou Elizondo 
Robert Hastings 
Dr Gary Nolan 
Jacques Vallée
Diana Pasulka
Red Panda Koala
Ross Coulthart
Ralph Blumenthal

George Knapp 

And thanks to citizenM hotels for lending us the space for us to do our own public hearing.

video_name: Abandoned Alone in an African Tribe
title: Abandoned Alone in an African Tribe
video_description:
Want to join us on an adventure next year? http://seek-discomfort.com/yes-theory 
Here's the deal.. After Ammar took Seekers on adventures this year and also sponsored Nelly Attar to climb K2, I would like to also say thank you to those who support us through Seek Discomfort this holiday by taking a small group of 3 of you who purchase from Seek this Holiday on an adventure somewhere next year. We will contact the 3 adventurers by January 31st. If you have already purchased this holiday, you're already good to go :) if you'd like a chance to join me, you know where to go! ⚡️ ⚡️ ⚡️ 

🙏🏼 Thank you for making these videos possible through your support of Seek Discomfort

When it comes to what happened at the end.. It really shook me, we felt with the local team that we'd really prepared the best we could but sometimes unexpected problems like this one can happen. We've checked several times and everyone there is fine, they were really just looking for me. Nothing like this had really happened before even though I have experience traveling to Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Mauritania and I understand that there are things you can and cannot do. I went home after this trip to mentally recuperate and recharge.

//

video_name: Crew Member MISSING During Investigation! | Mountain Monsters | Travel Channel
title: Crew Member MISSING During Investigation! | Mountain Monsters | Travel Channel
video_description:
The AIMS team is in Pendleton County, West Virginia hunting down a Bigfoot locally known as the Fire Ape. Folklore says that this creature is drawn to fire, furious with mankind for stealing it from them. After meeting with locals who have seen this Bigfoot coming out of the forest, the team knows they must construct a trap that utilizes fire in an attempt to capture it. The hunt turns into a nightmare when the team realizes their sound guy is missing -- likely TAKEN by the Fire Ape. In an attempt to distract the beast and save their lost crew member, the team sets off dozens of fireworks in the middle of the woods. But will it be enough?

video_description:
Andrew is in Panama City, joined by chef María de los Ángeles for a taste of the city's best street food. They enjoy a beef lung stew served with twice-fried plantains before downing chichemes, a drink made of mashed sweet corn, condensed milk, cinnamon, and vanilla. Finally, it's time for a hearty helping of "rompe colchon," or "mattress breaker," a smoothie that does more than quench thirst!

title: Uncovering the Mystery of the Mouthless Lady | Ghosts of Morgan City | Travel Channel
video_description:
When the police department of Morgan City, Louisiana is flooded by unusual emergency calls, they bring in a paranormal team to help. The team -- local paranormal investigator Jereme Leonard, former FBI agent Ben Hansen, and psychic medium Sarah Lemos -- investigate a mysterious mist they believe to be Ada LeBoeuf. Her spirit shapeshifts into a “Mouthless Lady” near the town's lake, and the team learns that her hauntings have spread throughout the rest of St. Mary Parish. During a heart-pounding investigation, the team captures a face in mist whom they believe is Ada herself. After talking with her spirit through the team's REM Pod, Ada clears her name as her husband's murderer.

video_name: Spicing It Up in Sri Lanka | Anthony Bourdain: No Reservations | Travel Channel
title: Spicing It Up in Sri Lanka | Anthony Bourdain: No Reservations | Travel Channel
video_description:
Anthony heads to the coastal city of Colombo, Sri Lanka, braving heat and body aches to get a first-taste experience of the country’s unique culinary and flavor traditions. For breakfast, it’s egg hoppers topped with seeni sambol -- a mix of onion, chili, tamarind; coconut sambol; and chicken curry. Then Anthony’s off to Rifka Catering, a no-frills operation serving delicious biryani -- a rice dish mixed with an array of toppings, seasoned with biryani marsala. Finally, Anthony is led by an aromatic trail of cardamom, nutmeg, and more to Barefoot Café, an eatery that serves traditional Sri Lankan food with the region’s signature spices at its forefront.

video_description:
Paranormal investigator Dave Schrader, psychic medium Cindy Kaza, and equipment expert Shane Pittman visit the haunted Morris-Jumel Mansion in New York City -- one of Hans Holzer’s most famous cases. In 1964, Holzer communicated with Stephen Jumel, a man who was supposedly killed by his wife Eliza. Reopening the case, the team suspects a darker presence is now in the home. As they communicate with Eliza, they encounter a terrifying presence, suggesting the mansion’s true hauntings might be more complex and sinister than they originally thought.

Paranormal investigator Dave Schrader, psychic medium Cindy Kaza, equipment expert Shane Pittman and researcher Gabe Roth investigate terrifyingly true hauntings from the recently discovered case files of America's first ghost hunter, Dr. Hans Holzer. Recognized as the ""father of the paranormal,"" Holzer's four-decades-long exploration into disturbing hauntings like the Amityville Horror house spawned legions of supernatural enthusiasts, more than 120 books and even inspired Dan Aykroyd to write Ghostbusters. For the first time ever, Holzer's daughter, Alexandra Holzer, reopens her father's most captivating case files -- along with thousands of his documents, letters, photographs and hours of chilling audio-visual recordings from as early as the 1950s. Equipped with this treasure trove of paranormal knowledge and state-of-the-art technology, the team compares their findings with Holzer's to see if their modern research sheds new light on these half-century-old investigations.

title: Reopening CHILLING 50-Year-Old Haunting - Full Episode Recap | The Holzer Files | Travel Channel
video_description:
Paranormal investigator Dave Schrader, psychic medium Cindy Kaza, and equipment expert Shane Pittman from The Holzer Files, with the help of Dr. Hans Holzer’s daughter Alexandra Holzer, reopen his 50-year-old case of paranormal activity at one of the oldest houses in Rye, N.Y. In 1963, Holzer recorded ghostly events at the Peck House, tied to Ladi Peck, a girl who died in a fire in 1884. Although a portrait seemed to calm her spirit in 1985, the team now finds similar activity at the nearby Knapp House. As the team investigates, they face chilling encounters: water mysteriously seeping from the ceiling, unseen forces grabbing their necks, and a sinister woman with blackened teeth.

Paranormal investigator Dave Schrader, psychic medium Cindy Kaza, equipment expert Shane Pittman and researcher Gabe Roth investigate terrifyingly true hauntings from the recently discovered case files of America's first ghost hunter, Dr. Hans Holzer. Recognized as the ""father of the paranormal,"" Holzer's four-decades-long exploration into disturbing hauntings like the Amityville Horror house spawned legions of supernatural enthusiasts, more than 120 books and even inspired Dan Aykroyd to write Ghostbusters. For the first time ever, Holzer's daughter, Alexandra Holzer, reopens her father's most captivating case files -- along with thousands of his documents, letters, photographs and hours of chilling audio-visual recordings from as early as the 1950s. Equipped with this treasure trove of paranormal knowledge and state-of-the-art technology, the team compares their findings with Holzer's to see if their modern research sheds new light on these half-century-old investigations.

Have you ever dreamed of exploring a hidden European gem, rich in history yet untouched by mass tourism? Discover the 10 best places to visit in Lithuania, a Baltic treasure trove of cultural wonders and natural beauty.

From the enchanting Hill of Witches in Juodkrantė to the vibrant coastal charm of Palanga, Lithuania offers a refreshing escape from overcrowded destinations. As we unveil these 10 best places to visit in Lithuania, you'll be captivated by the country's diverse landscapes and fascinating stories.

Discover the "10 Best Places To Visit IN LITHUANIA" in this captivating journey through one of Europe's hidden gems. From medieval castles to pristine beaches, Lithuania offers a diverse array of experiences for every traveler.

Our adventure begins in Vilnius, the charming capital, before taking us to Trakai, home to the iconic island castle. We'll explore Kaunas attractions, showcasing Lithuania's second-largest city's vibrant culture and unique architecture.

Our journey continues along the Baltic coast, from the Curonian Spit Lithuania to the lively resort town of Palanga. We'll then explore the picturesque Aukštaitija National Park, a haven for outdoor enthusiasts.

From the historic port city of Klaipėda to the charming Druskininkai spa town, we'll uncover Lithuania's diverse landscapes and rich heritage. This video showcases why these "10 Best Places To Visit IN LITHUANIA" should be on every traveler's bucket list, revealing the country's unique charm and unforgettable experiences.

These stunning fortresses, scattered across Czechia's enchanting landscapes, showcase the country's rich architectural heritage and historical intrigue. From the imposing Gothic structures to the elegant Renaissance palaces, each castle invites you to delve into centuries of royal history and cultural significance. 

Discover the "07 Most Beautiful Castles to Visit in Czechia" in our latest video, where we take you on a journey through some of the most enchanting and historically significant castles in the Czech Republic.
First, explore the imposing Karlštejn Castle, a Gothic masterpiece built by Emperor Charles IV to protect the crown jewels. Next, we visit the fairytale-like Hluboká Castle, renowned for its stunning white facade and picturesque gardens.

Then, delve into the rich history of Pernštejn Castle, often called the "Marble Castle" for its impressive stonework. The enchanting Český Krumlov Castle offers a glimpse into Renaissance and Baroque architecture, while the medieval Bouzov Castle captivates with its romantic charm.

In Moravian-Silesia, Hradec nad Moravicí stands out with its unique blend of Gothic and Renaissance styles, surrounded by serene landscapes. Lastly, we unveil the hidden gem of Bouzov Castle, a perfect destination for history enthusiasts and nature lovers alike.

25 Most Beautiful Places To Visit In The World | Ultimate Travel guide
#mostbeautifulplacesintheworld #beautifulplacesonearth #bestplacestovisit #traveldestinations 

Welcome to our grand tour of the 25 Most Beautiful Places to Visit on Earth. 
Brace yourself for a visual feast as we unveil destinations that are nothing short of miraculous from towering mountains wreathed in clouds to crystal-clear lagoons that whisper tales of tranquility. Each site has been handpicked not only for its breathtaking beauty but also for the unique stories and experiences it offers.

Begin your journey at the ethereal Plitvice Lakes National Park in Croatia, where waterfalls cascade into shimmering lakes. Then, venture to the rugged cliffs of Scotland’s Highlands, offering tales of history and panoramic views that stretch beyond the horizon. Marvel at the architectural wonder of Mont Saint Michel in France, rising majestically from tidal waters, and feel the raw, spiritual energy of Bagan with its skyline studded with ancient pagodas.

Experience the surreal landscapes of Monument Valley in the USA, with its towering red sandstone buttes set against vast, open skies. Drift through the peaceful canals of the Whitsundays in Australia, where the ocean meets white sand beaches in a perfect embrace of natural beauty.
Explore the lush, green expanses of the Cameron Highlands in Malaysia, teeming with flora and fauna, and soak in the vibrant hues of the Danxia landform’s geological wonders in China. Witness the dramatic fluctuations of Iceland’s geography, from spouting geysers to expansive ice fields, each site telling its own story of creation and change.

As the journey continues, discover the serenity of the Kuang Si Falls in Laos, where water flows over tiered limestone formations into crystal-clear pools below. Be inspired by the dynamic environment of Torres del Paine in Chile, a haven for trekkers with its breathtaking vistas and diverse ecosystems.

Each destination in '25 Most Beautiful Places to Visit on Earth' is carefully selected to inspire awe and wonder. This video is more than just a travel guide; it’s an invitation to experience the unparalleled beauty of the world. Welcome to our exploration of the 10 best Croatian islands to visit in 2024.
 
Croatia's stunning archipelago, part of the dazzling Adriatic Sea, is celebrated for its enchanting mix of serene landscapes and vibrant cultural heritage.

Sprinkled along Croatia’s sun-kissed coast, these islands offer a mosaic of breathtaking views, historic sites, and pristine beaches. From the energetic streets of Hvar to the tranquil shores of Vis, each island presents a unique journey into the heart of the Adriatic’s charm.

Escape to the enchanting Croatian islands! Discover the allure of Croatia's coast with our guide to the 10 best Croatian islands to visit in 2024. From the stunning beaches of Hvar to the rich history of Korčula, each island offers a unique blend of natural beauty and cultural treasures.

title: SWITZERLAND 🌧️ VIOLENT SUMMER STORM - INTERLAKEN - THE MOST BEAUTIFUL SWISS CITY
video_description:
◯  Home page of the Interlaken tourist-office  :
https://www.interlaken.ch/en/

📌 Location :   Interlaken ,  Switzerland
Date recorded:  AUGUST  7:30 PM  Monday
Weather: ⛅  12 °C | 53 °F 🌡

✉️ CONTACT  :  contact.touristchannel@gmail.com

Welcome my dear friends, today we will explore Interlaken under a violent summer rain, come with me to explore this jewel of the Swiss Alps, I hope you like it and I want you to accompany me to the end 🤗

Interlaken is a small town with a population of around 5,500 (a figure that may vary slightly depending on the sources and the specific year). Although the population is relatively small, the city has significant importance in the region due to tourism.

Tourism is Interlaken's main economic engine. Thanks to its spectacular natural scenery and access to various outdoor activities, Interlaken attracts a large number of tourists from all over the world every year.

Interlaken is a picturesque city located in the Bernese Oberland region of Switzerland, known for its spectacular scenery and varied opportunities for outdoor activities. Located between two lakes, Thun and Brienz, Interlaken is a popular destination for both tourists and nature and adventure enthusiasts.

 Important information about Interlaken:

 Location :
Interlaken is located between Lake Thun (to the west) and Lake Brienz (to the east), in the heart of the Swiss Alps. It is an ideal starting point for exploring the Jungfrau region, one of the most beautiful and accessible mountain areas in Switzerland.

Jungfrau Region:
Interlaken is a gateway to the Jungfrau region, which includes famous destinations such as the Jungfraujoch, known as the "Top of Europe". Here, tourists can admire impressive landscapes, including the Aletsch Glacier, the largest glacier in the Alps. Nearby towns such as Grindelwald, Lauterbrunnen and Wengen are easily accessible from Interlaken and offer spectacular alpine scenery.

Lakes Thun and Brienz:
Lake Thun: Lake Thun, located west of Interlaken, is larger and known for its medieval castles, such as Thun Castle and Oberhofen Castle, but also for the picturesque villages on the shore. Lake Brienz: Lake Brienz, east of Interlaken, is famous for its turquoise water and scenic boat cruises that offer great views of the Alps.

Tourist attractions:
Harder Kulm : This mountain peak, located at an altitude of 1,322 meters, offers a panoramic view of the city of Interlaken, the surrounding lakes and mountains. You can get here with a funicular.
Schynige Platte : This popular hiking destination offers impressive views of the Eiger, Mönch and Jungfrau mountain ranges.

Culture and traditions:
 Interlaken hosts many cultural events and festivals, including the Interlaken Folk Festival, where visitors can experience Swiss traditions through music, dance and folk costumes.Interlaken is an example of an Alpine city where tourism plays a dominant role, largely determining the local economic structure and dynamics.

Interlaken is a place that offers a unique combination of adventure, relaxation and nature exploration, suitable for both active travelers and those looking for unforgettable mountain scenery.

title: ISOLATED LIFE IN THE SWISS MOUNTAINS - ZINAL - A TRADITIONAL SWISS VILLAGE IN THE ALPS
video_description:
◯  Home page of the Zinal tourist-office  :
https://www.valdanniviers.ch/en/homepage.html

📌 Location :   Zinal ,  Switzerland
Date recorded:  AUGUST  7:30 PM  Monday
Weather: ⛅  12 °C | 53 °F 🌡

✉️ CONTACT  :  contact.touristchannel@gmail.com

Location and accessibility
Zinal is at an altitude of approximately 1,670 meters and is part of the commune of Anniviers.
Access to Zinal is via a mountain road that starts from Sierre, a town at the base of the valley.
It is a popular destination in both summer and winter, being known for its hiking activities and winter sports.Zinal is surrounded by five peaks over 4,000 meters: Weisshorn, Zinalrothorn, Dent Blanche, Ober Gabelhorn and Matterhorn, offering unforgettable views for visitors.

Winter sports
Skiing: Zinal is part of the Grimentz-Zinal ski area, which offers a variety of slopes for all levels, from beginners to advanced. The ski area reaches a maximum altitude of 2,900 meters.
Freeride: Zinal is known for its freeride areas, attracting experienced skiers and snowboarders.
Cross-country skiing and snowshoeing: The region offers numerous trails for cross-country skiing and snowshoeing.

Summer activities
Hiking: Zinal is a starting point for many hiking trails, including high altitude trails such as the famous "Tour du Cervin".Mountain Biking: There are numerous mountain biking trails that offer challenges for riders of all levels.Climbing: The surrounding peaks offer climbing routes of varying difficulty.

Natural attractions
Zinal Glacier: Near the resort is the Zinal Glacier, which can be explored on foot or on organized tours.
Mountain lakes: Lakes such as Lac de Moiry are accessible from Zinal and offer spectacular views and recreational opportunities.

Events
The traditional celebration "Fête de la Mi-Été": It is a popular event that takes place in the middle of summer and celebrates local traditions with parades, music and folk dances.The "Sierre-Zinal" cross-country race: One of the most famous mountain cross-country races in the world, attracting elite international participants. The route stretches for 31 kilometers, from Sierre to Zinal.

Accommodation and facilities
Zinal offers a wide range of accommodation options, from luxury hotels to mountain lodges and campsites.The resort has restaurants, shops and facilities for tourists, including sports equipment rental centers.

Culture and history
Zinal preserves the traditions of the Valais region, being a place where mountain culture and Swiss hospitality are very well preserved.In the Zinal area, there are also small museums or exhibitions that present local history and traditional mountain life.

Zinal is ideal for those looking for a combination of outdoor activities and relaxation in an impressive natural setting. It is a place where nature blends harmoniously with tradition and sports activities, offering a complete mountain holiday experience.

video_name: FRANCE - THE HIDDEN VILLAGES THAT NOBODY WANTS TO SHOW - A TREASURE ON FRENCH RIVIERA
title: FRANCE - THE HIDDEN VILLAGES THAT NOBODY WANTS TO SHOW - A TREASURE ON FRENCH RIVIERA
video_description:
◯  Home page of the CAGNES-SUR-MER tourist-office  :
https://tourisme.cagnes.fr/en/

📌 Location : CAGNES-SUR-MER , France
Date recorded:  AUGUST  1:30 PM
Weather: ⛅  31 °C | 87 °F 🌡

✉️ CONTACT  :  contact.touristchannel@gmail.com


The medieval village
Haut-de-Cagnes, a medieval village located at the top of the castle hill, is the historic part of the town of Cagnes-sur-Mer.

650 inhabitants have chosen to live in this district, classified as a "historic site" in 1948, which has managed to preserve the serenity of village life, outside the hectic pace of the Côte d'Azur.

Patina of centuries, stones steeped in history, shaded, narrow and flowery streets, unusual views of the Mediterranean and the Mercantour, everything contributes to retain the visitor in search of authenticity.

Unique site on the French Riviera
Haut-de-Cagnes has managed to both preserve the mystery of the strongholds of Provence and open up widely to visitors who roam it.

A maze of steep streets paved with pebbles, vaulted passageways, flower-decked stairs, eye-catching houses, unusual viewpoints, artists' studios, Haut-de-Cagnes reveals itself at every step...

The Church of Saint-Pierre and Saint-Paul
The church, which had become too small to contain all its faithful, was restored and enlarged in the 16th and 18th centuries.
The work completed in 1762 doubled the proportions with the higher nave visible in the right part, a main entrance portal was also added. It is visible from the church square behind the building. At the time, the parish of Cagnes had 1,200 souls.

THE HIDDEN VILLAGES THAT NOBODY WANTS TO SHOW - A TREASURE ON FRENCH RIVIERA

In the church, you can admire some religious paintings from the 18th century, including the canvas that adorns the high altar and represents the handing over of the keys to Saint-Pierre.
The paintings of the Stations of the Cross, produced by the painter Charles Barkev on the occasion of the 2000 Jubilee, offer the particularity of representing Cagnois from Haut-de-Cagnes who agreed to pose to illustrate the Passion of Christ.

When "The Rounded Hill"...
“Cagnes” is a name of Ligurian origin which means “inhabited place on a rounded hill”.

This rocky outcrop, which culminates at 91 meters above sea level, offered our ancestors an ideal surveillance and defense position, near a river and good land.

This place was first occupied by the Celto-Ligurians and then by the Gallo-Romans.

When Provence united with France in 1483, Cagnes became a border town on the only road leading to France from the States of Savoy.

From the 16th century, this border zone which entered into a cycle of great European wars was often looted and sacked.


The reigns of Louis XIV and Louis XV bring back wars and multiple invasions of the border area.

During the French Revolution, in 1790, Cagnes still had only 1,388 inhabitants, most of them peasants who lived from the cultivation of vines, olive trees, hemp, citrus fruits and early vegetables.

At the beginning of the 20th century, when Renoir came to settle in our city, from 1903 to his death in 1919, Cagnes was the capital of the canton with around 3,000 inhabitants.
Attracted by the celebrity of the Impressionist master, many painters who loved the Mediterranean light came to settle in this picturesque town which is nicknamed "The Montmartre of the Côte d'Azur", and which attracts celebrities from the world of arts and entertainment until the 1960s.

Among the most famous, stayed or lived in Haut-de-Cagnes, Pierre Auguste Renoir, Chaim Soutine, Foujita, Yves Klein, Georges Simenon (at 98, Montée de la Bourgade), Mouloudji (singer poet and composer), Suzy Solidor (singer and cabaret director), Georges Ulmer and Brigitte Bardot…

1 - Prague, the capital of the Czech Republic, is a European city of particular beauty, known for its Gothic, Baroque and Renaissance architecture. The city is often called the "Golden City" or the "City of a Hundred Bells" due to the impressive number of churches and historical buildings. The Charles Bridge, which crosses the Vltava River, is one of the oldest bridges in Europe and a symbol of the city. The Old Town Square is home to the famous Astronomical Clock, one of the oldest working clocks in the world. Today, Prague is an important cultural and tourist center, attracting millions of visitors annually who come to enjoy its unique charm and history.

2 -  Rome, the capital of Italy, is one of the most important cities in world history, being known as the "Eternal City". It was the center of the Roman Empire, which profoundly influenced Western civilization, culture, law and politics. Rome is famous for its ancient monuments, such as the Colosseum, a monumental amphitheater where gladiator fights took place, and the Roman Forum, the political and social heart of ancient Rome. The Pantheon, with its impressive dome, is one of the best-preserved buildings in Ancient Rome.Rome is also known for its baroque fountains, such as the Trevi Fountain, and its vibrant squares, such as Piazza Navona. The city harmoniously combines the old and the new, being an important cultural, artistic and gastronomic center that attracts millions of tourists annually.

3 - Vienna, the capital of Austria, is a city with a rich history and a leading cultural center in Europe. Known as the "City of Music" due to its close links with famous composers such as Mozart, Beethoven and Strauss, Vienna was and is a focal point for classical music and opera. Schönbrunn Palace, the summer residence of the imperial family, is one of the most impressive examples of Baroque architecture and a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The Hofburg Palace, the official residence of the Habsburg monarchs, today houses several museums and is a symbol of imperial power. With a unique combination of imperial history, artistic culture and modern life, Vienna annually attracts millions of visitors from all over the world.

4 - Budapest, the capital of Hungary, is a spectacular city located on the banks of the Danube, formed by the union of three historical cities: Buda, Pesta and Óbuda. It is known for its impressive architecture, picturesque landscapes and rich history. The Parliament of Budapest, one of the largest legislative buildings in the world, is a superb example of neo-Gothic architecture and a major attraction of the city. The Chain Bridge, which connects Buda to Pest, is one of the most famous symbols of the city. Budapest is also famous for its thermal baths, such as the Széchenyi Bath, one of the largest thermal bath complexes in Europe. With a unique combination of history, impressive architecture and cultural traditions, Budapest is an important tourist center and a top destination in Europe.

5 - Ljubljana, the capital of Slovenia, is a picturesque and vibrant city known for its relaxed atmosphere and impressive architecture. Although small compared to other European capitals, Ljubljana harmoniously blends cultural and historical influences with modernity. Ljubljana Castle, located on a hill overlooking the city, is one of the most emblematic points of attraction. The castle offers superb views of the city and hosts exhibitions on local history.
The Ljubljanica River, which runs through the city, is surrounded by lively squares, historic bridges and café terraces. The Dragon Bridge, decorated with dragon statues, is a symbol of the city, and the Triple Bridge (Tromostovje), created by the architect Jože Plečnik, is an outstanding example of urban engineering. The city is famous for its ecological initiatives, being designated the Green Capital of Europe in 2016. With a lively nightlife, green parks and a friendly atmosphere, Ljubljana is an increasingly popular destination in Central Europe.

ANDALUCIA - WONDERS OF THE WORLD - A REGION FULL OF HISTORY AND TRADITION

1 - Seville, the jewel of Andalusia, is a city where history comes alive at every turn. From the grandeur of the Gothic Cathedral, where Christopher Columbus rests, to the splendor of the Real Alcázar palace, a charming blend of Moorish and Christian influences, Seville is a veritable open-air museum. The city pulses with flamenco rhythms and its streets are animated by nightlife, delicious tapas and unforgettable festivities such as the Feria de Abril. With lively squares, picturesque landscapes and a deep cultural heritage, Seville captivates with a unique combination of tradition and passion.

2 - Ronda, a spectacular city in the province of Málaga, Spain, is renowned for its dramatic scenery and fascinating history. Perched on a rocky plateau, Ronda is bisected by the spectacular El Tajo gorge, over which arches the Puente Nuevo, an iconic bridge that offers stunning views of the valley below. The city is a cradle of Andalusian culture, with a bullring considered one of the oldest in Spain and traditional white houses reflecting Moorish influences. 

3 - Córdoba, a charming city in the heart of Andalusia, Spain, is a window to the splendor of the Moorish world. Its historic center is home to the Mezquita-Catedral, a unique architectural masterpiece that combines a large Islamic mosque with a Christian cathedral. The narrow, cobbled streets of the Jewish Quarter, filled with colorful flowers and hidden courtyards, invite exploration. Córdoba was once a cultural and intellectual center of medieval Europe, and still exudes an air of sophistication and mystery. 

4 - Frigiliana, a picturesque village located on the southern coast of Spain, in the province of Málaga, is one of the most beautiful examples of Andalusian architecture. With bright white houses, narrow streets, paved with mosaics and colorful flowers at every corner, Frigiliana looks like something out of a story. The old town, known for its Moorish influences, offers spectacular views of the Mediterranean Sea and surrounding mountains. Rich in tradition and culture, Frigiliana annually hosts the Three Cultures Festival, celebrating the region's Christian, Muslim and Jewish heritage. 

5 - Málaga, located on the southern coast of Spain, is a vibrant and lively city that combines history with modernity in a fascinating way. This historic port, the birthplace of Pablo Picasso, boasts a rich cultural offering, including the Museo Picasso and the Alcazaba, a well-preserved Moorish fortress. The city streets are alive with tapas bars, sunny beaches and colorful markets. Málaga is also famous for its festivals, dynamic nightlife and delicious gastronomy, including specialties such as espetos (grilled sardines). 

6 - Estepona, located on the Costa del Sol in southern Spain, is a charming destination that combines traditional Andalusian atmosphere with an idyllic Mediterranean climate. Known for its beautiful fine sand beaches and crystal clear waters, Estepona also offers a picturesque old town with cobbled streets, white houses adorned with colorful flowers and quiet squares. The town boasts attractive public gardens and a lively marina where restaurants and bars serve delicious fish and seafood. In addition, Estepona is recognized for its local celebrations and cultural events, which bring regional traditions and gastronomy to life.

Discover MOUSTIERS-SAINTE-MARIE, one of the most beautiful and spectacular villages in France

One of the most beautiful villages in France

Since 1981, Moustiers-Sainte-Marie has been listed among the Most Beautiful Villages in France. Church, ramparts, chapels, aqueduct, fountains, alliances of water and stone, pastel tones of tiles and tuff shape a homogeneous and lively architectural ensemble. The gentle way of life that emerges naturally encourages us to respect and enhance this place, to discover it and protect it. The work of the land, perpetrated for centuries, is the link between the history and the future of the village.

Authentic and lively

Today, Moustiers has around 700 inhabitants. The heart of its economy revolves around tourism and the earthenware tradition. The reception capacity in the town is significant. In addition to 750 camping pitches and a holiday village, 130 hotel rooms in the village centre or on the outskirts, around twenty gîtes and guest rooms and more than 50 furnished accommodations, it is easy to discover the local wonders beyond a fleeting crossing. The various services will satisfy all desires and all budgets.

On the commercial side, the shops of artists and craftsmen rub shoulders with local services.

On the food side, around twenty restaurants satisfy gourmets and gourmands, lovers of refined gastronomy, brasseries or local cuisine.

A village anchored in the Verdon Regional Natural Park and the Haute-Provence Geopark.

Moustiers-Sainte-Marie is part of the Verdon Regional Natural Park, spanning the two departments of Var and Alpes de Haute Provence, which extends over 46 municipalities and includes seven large landscape areas. This diversity of ecosystems gives the park a rich and varied natural heritage: vultures, bats, chamois, roe deer and endemic flora. The headquarters of the Verdon Regional Natural Park is located in the municipality of Moustiers.
www.parcduverdon.fr

Gorges du Verdon

Moustiers is also located in the territory of the UNESCO Haute-Provence Geopark. This nature reserve, listed by UNESCO, extends over 60 municipalities in the Alpes de Haute-Provence department. Many natural and geological sites allow you to discover the last 300 million years of Earth's history.
www.geoparchauteprovence.com

The mountains rock The cliffs on which the village is built and those dominating it formed natural lines of defense, but Moustiers also protected itself behind ramparts as for many villages, built in the Middle Ages.

Pierre de Pratis, commendatory prior, ordered in 1336 the enlargement of the church; the axis of the nave was not respected and we do not know if the prior wanted to incline the choir in the direction of Jerusalem or recall the position of the head of Christ on the cross. The current altar is a fourth century sarcophagus in white marble representing the passage of the Red Sea.

title: ALSACE - THE AUTHENTIC VILLAGE OF BEAUTY AND THE BEAST - THE MOST BEAUTIFUL PLACES IN THE WORLD
video_description:
📌 Location :  1 - Colmar  2 - Ehuiseheim
Date recorded:  AUGUST 2024   6:17 PM
Weather: ⛅  29 °C | 84 °F 🌡

◯  Home page of the Bormes les Mimosas tourist-office  :
https://www.bormeslesmimosas.com/

✉️ CONTACT  :  contact.touristchannel@gmail.com

The eastern part of France, right on the border with Germany, is home to the beautiful Alsace, considered by many to be one of the most beautiful regions in Europe. Characterised by its canals and beautiful half-timbered houses, this region also stands out for its succulent cuisine that perfectly blends French cuisine with traditional German recipes. If you are planning a getaway to the east of France, at Civitatis we explain what to see in Alsace.


1 - Colmar is the quintessential Alsatian village. Its romantic canals attract hundreds of thousands of tourists every year. These visitors also come in search of the colourful, typically Alsatian houses, which are decorated in bright pastel colours.

Precisely because of its network of canals, anyone who visits Colmar cannot miss the district of La Petite Venise or Little Venice. Walking through this area will surely make you feel like you are in a film. And no wonder, since the directors of the feature film Beauty and the Beast were inspired by the architecture of Colmar and other nearby towns to recreate the fictional village in which the animated film takes place.

Walt Disney himself had French ancestry – his roots can be traced back to the tiny dairy town of Isigny-sur-Mer in Normandy, where his ancestors became the Lords d’Isigny, before moving to England and anglicising it to Disney. And France’s Rococo interiors and romantic châteaux have inspired many a Disney set. So when it came to creating the 1991 animated version of Beauty and the Beast, the producers could think of no better setting for Belle’s home than Alsace.

The streets Belle calls home in the movie are almost identical to some of those seen in Colmar, Riquewihr and Ribeauvillé, all within a one-hour drive of the region’s main city, Strasbourg. She is portrayed as a conflicted outsider who longs to break free from the beautiful, yet predictable, small town she lives in – but when her plans are unexpectedly sidelined and she finds herself trapped in the château of a formidable beast, she gets a little more adventure than she’d bargained for.

2 - Stroll through the cobbled streets of Eguisheim, listed among the Most Beautiful Villages in France. A charming little village, typically Alsatian, with its old houses with pointed roofs, bright colours and half-timbered façades. "

Eguisheim is an essential stop during your stay in Alsace!

Located at the southern exit of Colmar, Eguisheim has been classified as one of the "Most Beautiful Villages in France" since 2003 and won the title of "Favorite Village of the French" in 2013 during the France 2 show presented by Stéphane Bern.

This medieval village is popular for its modest size, its unique architecture, its profusion of flowers in the summer, but also for its authentic charm during Christmas time when many activities are offered around the Christmas market.

Eguisheim takes its claim to fame from its architectural ensemble, preserved from the ravages of history and intelligently preserved.
Built around its castle, this medieval city unfolds in concentric circles. In this original village, you will discover fountains, courtyards and a church housing a "Vierge Ouvrante" from the 13th century.

It will be good to stroll along the alleys and admire the colorful palette of the houses where you can decipher the very old inscriptions on the door lintels.

In addition, from Colmar you can visit the nearby German city of Freiburg im Breisgau, considered the gateway to the Black Forest in Germany.

Bormes Les Mimosas is not a village, it is a real paradise of flowers, a unique medieval village, on the French Riviera, I usually visit this village at least once a year, this wonderful village is a real hidden pearl on the French Riviera, the streets its narrow and full of flowers, its coquettish and beautiful houses make the charm of this wonderful one unforgettable, come with me to discover this village and I promise you will not miss it 🤗

Provençal pearl nestled between sea and mountains, full of treasures to discover. Dive into an adventure where nature and culture meet to create unforgettable memories
 
Discover Bormes les Mimosas Your Next Paradise - A Flowery medieval village in the south of France  

Bormes-les-Mimosas is a small village in the Var clinging to the side of a hill, a sort of flowery balcony over an intense blue Mediterranean... Lower down, Le Lavandou and its beaches, the fort of Brégançon not far from the open sea then the sunny coasts of the Côte d'Azur.Bormes-les-Mimosas, a superb flowery village on the coast, has an enormous variety of different flowers, including the famous mimosas.

BORMES LES MIMOSAS - RELAXING SUMMER WALK IN A FLOWER PARADISE

The medieval village :

Heritage of the 12th century, referenced among the most beautiful sites in France, the village of Bormes les Mimosas is an essential stopover for lovers of old stones and history enthusiasts!

 Bormes-les-Mimosas is located in the department of Var in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region. This French commune is located on the edge of the Mediterranean and in the southern part of the Moorish massif. Like any locality in the region, the climate is Mediterranean with high heat in July.

The tourist attractions of this city are many. The most important of these is the old castle which is located on a hill. Then comes St. Francis Square where you can see a statue of St. Francis de Paul, a famous monk who lived there in the fifteenth century.

In Bormes-les-Mimosas, the maximum temperature during the hottest months (July and August) is 29°C and the minimum temperature during the coldest months (December, January and February) is 3°C. The city further records around 2850 hours of sunshine per year and around 58 rainy days per year.

Saint Trophyme Church: was built in the 18th century. Its architecture is predominantly Romanesque. Many chamber music concerts are held here.

Bormes les Mimosas the flower village on the French coast

The village of Bormes-les Mimosas has been called one of the most beautiful villages of the southern French coast of the Mediterranean. It is located at Côte d´Azur between Hyères and St. Tropez. Bormes is built against a hill, the foothills of the “Massif des Maures”. It has a beautiful view of the sea and the Île d’Or, the islands near Hyères. The Grand Duke of Luxembourg and the French Presidents were often guests in Bormes.

Bormes les Mimosas, a highlight during your holiday
Why is Bormes so special? In fact, everything is special about Bormes. The village is authentic and consists of narrow medieval streets and charming squares beautifully paved. In the alleys are shops, boutiques and art galleries. Due to it being built on a mountain, there are many steps and passages that make it extra beautiful. In addition, Bormes-les-Mimosas is one big flower show. The houses, alleys and squares are covered with beautiful plants and shrubs. It is really beautiful to see. Especially in the evening, when all the lights are on. It is one of the ‘plus beaux villages fleuris de France’, or one of the most beautiful flowered villages in France.

Foroglio is a real architectural jewel, hence the name, the village of the seven dwarfs from the story Snow White by the Brothers Grimm .

SWITZERLAND ,THE LIFE IN THE MOST ISOLATED SWISS VILLAGES , FOROGLIO , A LITTLE CORNER OF PARADISE

Foroglio is in the heart of the Bavona Valley, one of the wildest and best preserved valleys in the Swiss Alps. It is accessible via a scenic but rather narrow and winding mountain road.

Foroglio is a picturesque village located in the Bavona Valley in the canton of Ticino, Switzerland. Here are some important information about this place:

Geography and Nature
1. Location : Foroglio is in the heart of the Bavona Valley, one of the wildest and best preserved valleys in the Swiss Alps. It is accessible via a scenic but rather narrow and winding mountain road.

2. Foroglio Waterfall : One of the main attractions of the village is the Foroglio waterfall, which falls from a height of about 110 meters. It offers spectacular scenery and is a major tourist attraction.

3. Natural Landscapes : The Bavona Valley is known for its dramatic landscapes with steep cliffs, dense forests and a rich diversity of flora and fauna.

Culture and History
1. Traditions : Foroglio and its surroundings preserve the old traditions of the Ticino region. The stone houses and paved road are examples of traditional architecture.
2. Economy : The village was traditionally an agricultural and pastoral community with an economy based on animal husbandry and cheese production. Today, tourism plays an important role in the economy.
3. Heritage Conservation : Foroglio is part of Switzerland's cultural heritage, being an outstanding example of a traditional mountain settlement.

Tourism and Activities
1. Hiking and Excursions : The area is popular for hiking, offering various routes that lead through spectacular mountain scenery and traditional villages. The routes are varied in difficulty and duration.
2. Photography : Due to its impressive natural landscapes, Foroglio is a favorite place for nature and landscape photography.
3. Gastronomy : Visitors can enjoy traditional Ticino dishes in local restaurants, many of which use local ingredients.

Accessibility
1. Transport : Access to Foroglio is mainly by car, through the Bavona Valley. There are also limited public transport options, but these may require advance planning.
2. Accommodation : There are accommodation possibilities both in Foroglio and in nearby towns, ranging from traditional guesthouses to mountain huts.

Foroglio is a special place, offering a unique combination of stunning natural landscapes, well-preserved cultural traditions and opportunities for outdoor recreation.

My opinion about Foroglio is that this village is a unique place on this planet, if you have the opportunity I recommend you visit it, one of the most beautiful mountain villages I have visited and I hope you will like it too, if you have any questions or curiosities you can write in the comments and I will answer you kindly, with lots of love and respect, Sebastian

GRIMAUD IS THE MOST FLOWERY VILLAGE Y EVER SEEN IN MY LIFE  , THE MOST BEAUTIFUL VILLAGES OF FRANCE

The charm of a village, The village of Grimaud combines the charm of Provence of yesteryear and the medieval stories kept secret by its Castle. Immerse yourself in the heart of the authenticity of Grimaud and go back the centuries along the flowery paths.

Grimaud attracts tourists from all over the world due to its authentic charm, local gastronomy and proximity to popular destinations such as Saint-Tropez.

The monuments of Grimaud make you feel the past but not only... The cobbled streets, the stone walls tell stories that they are perhaps the last to know. It resonates with the secrets of Grimaud.

Lose yourself in the alleys, a thousand stories have happened there. It's up to you to imagine them.

Grimaud, in the Gulf of Saint-Tropez, is a village proudly displaying the colors of Provence. A Provence that is part of a medieval atmosphere, with its houses, its alleys, its Castle... The latter is the best known of the monuments in Grimaud, but did you know that it was far from being the only heritage building?

When summer arrives, it brings with it the blooming bougainvillea.

And what a wonder! The buildings of the old village are then adorned with a tailor-made purple dress to decorate the doors and windows of the houses.

Some bougainvilleas even climb a whole section of the facade. They are looking for the sun, to sunbathe every time!

It is a beautiful shrub that is often found in the Mediterranean, it is rare to find it in colder regions because it does not resist frost (a bit like the inhabitants of the south, it must be admitted).

A village flowered by its inhabitants
Every year, every season, the inhabitants of the old village delight us with their plantations which mingle, gently, with the houses, the alleys.

We nicknamed them among ourselves: “the village gardeners”.

It is impossible to miss the bougainvilleas during your visit. The best time to discover them is between the end of May/July. They may bloom again after summer as well.

Find the "bougainvillea walk" where around thirty shrubs are referenced and admire them in the alleys of Grimaud.

A village blessed by the gods
The heart of the perched village, wonderfully restored, has kept all its authenticity: cobbled streets, facades with vaulted arcades, pastel windows with flowery shutters, squares with bougainvillea essences. Unmissable, the discovery tour of the village, its churches and chapels bears witness to a rich historical past, traces of which can be found in the Museum of Popular Arts and Traditions.

When the roads shaded by pine trees give way to large expanses of vines. When those winding roads end up guiding you over steep heights. When with your fingertips you feel these old stones full of history. The smell of bougainvillea scratches my nose, I walk from cobblestone to cobblestone, I follow these vaulted arcades. Grimaud, the radiant, Grimaud the fragrant. Labyrinthine streets, graceful houses, I discover Grimaud, the discreet one, Grimaud the secret alcove. Time has left its mark on these villages which have managed to keep their heritage without distorting it. Medieval images take shape, we happily invent a life for ourselves. Why is Positano famous?
Find out what to see in Positano: 10 attractions not to be missed
Positano is a splendid town on the Amalfi Coast, famous for its colorful houses overlooking the sea and its enchanting beaches. Among the main attractions are the Church of Santa Maria Assunta, the picturesque alleys and the excellent local cuisine.

It's hard to find a better subject for a photographer: Positano is a postcard from every angle.
Once a peaceful fishing village, it is one of the most fashionable destinations for famous people and travelers from around the world. It began to attract a large share of tourists in the 1950s, especially after John Steinbeck published an essay about this place in May 1953 where he wrote: “Positano affects us deeply. It’s a dream place that doesn’t seem real to you while you’re there and it becomes nostalgically real when you leave.”

The origins of this charming place are mixed between history and legend. As in the past, myths are the remedy for the lack of actual data: one of them attributes the founding of Positano to Poseidon, the god of the sea, for the love of the nymph Pasitea.

It is an almost impossible city: on the slopes of the Lattari Mountains, it forms a colorful landscape that overlooks the Mediterranean Sea with a view that extends to the sea, the islands and the other centers of the Costiera Amalfitana.

Positano itself is a sight to visit: the alleys are narrow passages between houses and steep staircases that intersect the alleys. Only one road crosses the town, Viale Pasitea, the rest of the village is only accessible on foot, between shops, art galleries, artisan workshops, restaurants, cafes and bougainvillea waterfalls.

Positano
Marina Grande beach is the most famous and frequented and offers one of the most beautiful panoramas of the characteristic cascade of colorful houses. A panoramic path – which runs along the sea and the Saracen watchtowers – leads to Fornillo beach, for those who prefer less crowded places.

Pearl of the Amalfi Coast in southern Italy, Positano clings to the rocks overlooking the Mediterranean Sea. Between Sorrento and Amalfi, Positano is the most touristy village on the Italian coast south of Naples. Historically linked to the Republic of Amalfi, Positano owes its wealth to maritime trade with the Near and Middle East in the 16th century.
From the 20th century, thanks to its idyllic location, the village became a vacation spot for the wealthy and artists, a symbol of la dolce vita made in Italy. Today luxury villas, hotels, fashion stores pile up in a crowded historic center, but the charm of Positano, its beaches and its splendid viewpoints, still operates. Treat yourself to an Italian vacation between sea and mountains.

According to legend, Neptune, the god of the sea in Roman mythology, built this little corner of paradise in homage to a nymph with whom he was madly in love.

Moreover, Positano has been listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1997!

Therefore, I advise you to take a short day to visit Positano during your stay on the Amalfi Coast. The opportunity to make a stop between Sorrento and Amalfi, for example. If possible, avoid leaving during the summer: choose a trip out of season. Particularly in spring (April and May) and at the beginning of autumn (October).

THE ELEGANT LIFE IN A FRENCH VILLAGE 

Saint-Paul-de-Vence is a picturesque medieval village located in the south of France in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region. This is one of the oldest and most beautiful fortified villages in Provence, known for its rich history, artistic culture and picturesque landscapes.

### Important information about Saint-Paul-de-Vence

1. **History:**
 - **Foundation:** The village was founded in the 9th century, but became an important strategic and military point in the 16th century, when King François I ordered its fortification to protect the region from Spanish invasions.
 - **Fortifications:** The city walls were built in 1544 and remain largely intact to this day. They offer an impressive view of the surrounding landscape.

2. **Culture and Art:**
 - **Artist Colony:** Since the early 20th century, Saint-Paul-de-Vence has attracted many famous artists, writers and actors, including Marc Chagall, who lived here and painted many of his works . Today, the village is home to numerous art galleries and workshops.
 - **Maeght Foundation:** It is a museum of modern and contemporary art located near the village, founded in 1964 by Aimé and Marguerite Maeght. The foundation houses an impressive collection of works by artists such as Joan Miró, Alberto Giacometti and Marc Chagall.

3. **Tourist Attractions:**
 - **La Colombe d'Or:** A famous hotel and restaurant that has hosted many personalities from the world of art and film. The hotel is known for its art collection, which includes works by Picasso and Matisse.
 - **Collegiate Church:** Built in the 14th century, this church is an outstanding example of Gothic and Romanesque architecture. Its interior includes a beautiful baroque altar.
 - **Narrow Streets and Cubic Stone:** Walking through the narrow and cobbled streets of the village offers a foray into the medieval atmosphere, with numerous craft shops and art galleries.

4. **Landscapes and Nature:**
 - **Panoramic View:** From the fortified walls and various vantage points, visitors can enjoy spectacular views of the surrounding valleys, plains and the Mediterranean Sea.
 - **Gardens and Parking:** The village is surrounded by lush gardens and olive groves, which add extra rural charm.

5. **Events and Festivals:**
 - **Art Festivals:** Saint-Paul-de-Vence hosts various cultural events and art festivals throughout the year, thus attracting tourists from all over the world.

### Recommendations for Visitors

- **Time to Visit:** Spring and autumn are the best times to visit as the weather is pleasant and the village is less crowded than in the summer season.
- **Transportation:** The village is accessible from Nice and other major cities on the Côte d'Azur. The best way to get there is by car or bus.
- **Accommodation:** There are a variety of accommodation options, from luxury hotels to traditional guesthouses, offering an authentic Provençal experience.

Saint-Paul-de-Vence is an ideal destination for those who want to enjoy the natural beauty, history and rich culture of the Provence region.
